article.description: Connecticut routed West Virginia 71-41 Tuesday night, but the Huskies' streak of 11 straight regular-season Big East titles ended.
article.headline: Huskies get No. 3 seed for Big East tournament
article.linkText: UConn's time as Big East champ runs out
article.story:
MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Connecticut routed West Virginia 71-41
Tuesday night, but the Huskies' streak of 11 straight regular-season Big East titles ended.

Ann Strother scored 19 points for No. 14 UConn (20-7, 13-3),
which finished in a second-place tie with No. 10 Notre Dame in the
Big East. The Irish own the tiebreaker, meaning UConn will get the No. 3 seed in the conference tournament.

Ninth-ranked Rutgers clinched the regular-season championship
with a 51-39 win over Villanova Tuesday night. The Irish beat Seton
Hall.

The Huskies had won or shared every Big East regular-season
title since the 1993-94 season. They shared the crown with Rutgers
in the 1998-99 season.

Connecticut, coming off a 51-48 loss at Boston College on
Saturday, couldn't pull away from West Virginia until the second
half.

UConn led 32-25 at halftime but scored 17 of the next 21 points.

West Virginia sophomore Meg Bulger clinched her first Big East
scoring title (19.5) despite being limited to eight points. No West
Virginia player finished in double figures.

The Mountaineers (16-11, 7-9) ended the regular season with
their two worst losses of the season, falling to Notre Dame 82-57
on Saturday.

Connecticut leads the all-time series 15-1 and has outscored
West Virginia by an average of 34.5 points. The Mountaineers' only
win in the series was in 1982 in their first meeting.

	   With the win, the Huskies avoided losing consecutive games for
the first time since 1992-93.

The Big East conference tournament begins Saturday in Hartford, Conn. The top four teams earned first-round byes.
